    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "This class provides convenience methods for drawing radial or linear (axial) gradients for rectangles and "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/appkit/nsbezierpath"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " objects. It also supports primitive methods that let you customize the shape of the gradient fill. A gradient consists of two or more color changes over the range of the gradient shape. When creating a gradient object, you specify the colors and their locations relative to the start and end of the gradient. This combination of color and location is known as a "
            },
            {
              "type": "newTerm",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "color stop"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". During drawing, the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/appkit/nsgradient"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object uses the color stop information to compute color changes for you and passes that information to the Quartz shading functions. "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Because the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/appkit/nsgradient"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " class uses Quartz shadings, drawing is handled by computing the colors at a given point mathematically. This technique results in smooth gradients regardless of the resolution of the target device. "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "For more information about gradients and their appearance, see "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "title": "Gradients",
              "destination": "https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/documentation/GraphicsImaging/Conceptual/drawingwithquartz2d/dq_shadings/dq_shadings.html#//apple_ref/doc/uid/TP30001066-CH207"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " in "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "title": "Quartz 2D Programming Guide",
              "destination": "https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/documentation/GraphicsImaging/Conceptual/drawingwithquartz2d/Introduction/Introduction.html#//apple_ref/doc/uid/TP30001066"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". "
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
